# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thrift-idl
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] It uses a remote procedure call (RPC) framework and combines a software stack with a code generation engine to build cross-platform services.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] Thrift can connect applications written in a variety of languages and frameworks, including ActionScript, C, C++, C#, Cocoa, Delphi, Erlang, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Objective-C, OCaml, Perl, PHP, Python, Ruby, Elixir, Rust, Scala, Smalltalk, and Swift.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] The implementation was described in an April 2007 technical paper released by Facebook, now hosted on Apache.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] Thrift includes a complete stack for creating clients and servers.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] The top part is generated code from the Thrift definition.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] From this file, the services generate client and processor codes.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] In contrast to built-in types, created data structures are sent as a result of generated code.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] The protocol and transport layer are part of the runtime library.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] With Thrift, it is possible to define a service and change the protocol and transport without recompiling the code.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] Besides the client part, Thrift includes server infrastructure such as blocking, non-blocking, and multi-threaded servers.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] The underlying I/O part of the stack is implemented differently for different programming languages.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] Thrift is written in C++, but can create code for some other programming languages.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] To create a Thrift service, one has to write Thrift files that describe it, generate the code in the destination language, write some code to start the server, and call it from the client.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] Thrift will generate the code out of this descriptive information.
[src:thrift-idl/apache-thrift] For instance, in Java, the `PhoneType` will be `enum` inside the `Phone` class.
[src:thrift-idl/interface-description-language] An **interface description language** or **interface definition language** (**IDL**) is a generic term for a language that lets a program or object written in one language communicate with another program written in an unknown language.
[src:thrift-idl/interface-description-language] IDLs are usually used to describe data types and interfaces in a language-independent way, for example, between those written in C++ and those written in Java.
[src:thrift-idl/interface-description-language] IDLs are commonly used in remote procedure call software.
[src:thrift-idl/interface-description-language] In these cases the machines at either end of the *link* may be using different operating systems and computer languages.
[src:thrift-idl/interface-description-language] IDLs offer a bridge between the two different systems.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] In computer science, **marshalling** or **marshaling** (US spelling) is the process of transforming the memory representation of an object into a data format suitable for storage or transmission, especially between different runtimes.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] It is typically used when data must be moved between different parts of a computer program or from one program to another.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling simplifies complex communications, because it allows using *composite objects* instead of being restricted to *primitive objects*.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is sometimes used as synonymous with serializing, while serialization is actually one step in the process of marshalling an object.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling and serialization might thus be done differently, although some form of serialization is usually used to do marshalling.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] The term *deserialization* is somewhat similar to *un*-marshalling a dry object "on the server side", i.e., demarshalling (or unmarshalling) to get a live object back: the serialized object is transformed into an internal data structure, i.e., a live object within the target runtime.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] It usually corresponds to the exact inverse process of marshalling, although sometimes both ends of the process trigger specific business logic.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] The accurate definition of marshalling differs across programming languages such as Python, Java, and .NET, and in some contexts, is used interchangeably with serialization.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] To "serialize" an object means to convert its state into a byte stream in such a way that the byte stream may be converted back into a copy of the object, which is unmarshalling in essence.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Different programming languages either make or don’t make the distinction between the two concepts.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] In the Java-related RFC 2713, marshalling is used when serializing objects for remote invocation.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] An object that is marshalled records the state of the original object and it contains the codebase (*codebase* here refers to a list of URLs where the object code can be loaded from, and not source code).
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, in order to convert the object state and codebase(s), unmarshalling must be done.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshaller interface automatically converts the marshalled data containing codebase(s) into an executable Java object in JAXB.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Any object that can be deserialized can be unmarshalled.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is used within implementations of different remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms, where it is necessary to transport data between processes and/or between threads.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] In Microsoft's Component Object Model (COM), interface pointers must be marshalled when crossing COM apartment boundaries.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] In the .NET Framework, the conversion between an unmanaged type and a CLR type, as in the P/Invoke process, is also an example of an action that requires marshalling to take place.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Additionally, marshalling is used extensively within scripts and applications that use the XPCOM technologies provided within the Mozilla application framework.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] The Mozilla Firefox browser is a popular application built with this framework, that additionally allows scripting languages to use XPCOM through XPConnect (Cross-Platform Connect).
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] In the Microsoft Windows family of operating systems the entire set of device drivers for Direct3D are kernel-mode drivers.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] The user-mode portion of the API is handled by the DirectX runtime provided by Microsoft.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] This is an issue because calling kernel-mode operations from user-mode requires performing a system call, and this inevitably forces the CPU to switch to "kernel mode".
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] This is a slow operation, taking on the order of microseconds to complete.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] During this time, the CPU is unable to perform any operations.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] As such, minimizing the number of times this switching operation must be performed would optimize performance to a substantive degree.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Linux OpenGL drivers are split in two: a kernel-driver and a user-space driver.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] The user-space driver does all the translation of OpenGL commands into machine code to be submitted to the GPU.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] To reduce the number of system calls, the user-space driver implements marshalling.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] If the GPU's command buffer is full of rendering data, the API could simply store the requested rendering call in a temporary buffer and, when the command buffer is close to being empty, it can perform a switch to kernel-mode and add a number of stored commands all at once.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling data requires some kind of data transfer, which leverages a specific data format to be chosen as the serialization target.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] XML is one such format and means of transferring data between systems.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Microsoft, for example, uses it as the basis of the file formats of the various components (Word, Excel, Access, PowerPoint, etc.) of the Microsoft Office suite (see Office Open XML).
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] While this typically results in a verbose wire format, XML's fully-bracketed "start-tag", "end-tag" syntax allows provision of more accurate diagnostics and easier recovery from transmission or disk errors.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] In addition, because the tags occur repeatedly, one can use standard compression methods to shrink the content—all the Office file formats are created by zipping the raw XML.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Alternative formats such as JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) are more concise, but correspondingly less robust for error recovery.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Once the data is transferred to a program or an application, it needs to be converted back to an object for usage.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, unmarshalling is generally used in the receiver end of the implementations of Remote Method Invocation (RMI) and Remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms to unmarshal transmitted objects in an executable form.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB or Java Architecture for XML Binding is the most common framework used by developers to marshal and unmarshal Java objects.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB provides for the interconversion between fundamental data types supported by Java and standard XML schema data types.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` is the framework used by C# developers to marshal and unmarshal C# objects.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] One of the advantages of C# over Java is that C# natively supports marshalling due to the inclusion of `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` class.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Java, on the other hand requires a non-native glue code in the form of JAXB to support marshalling.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] An example of unmarshalling is the conversion of an XML representation of an object to the default representation of the object in any programming language.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshalling is the process of converting the XML representation to the default executable Java representation, and running that very code to get a consistent, live object back.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Had a different format been chosen, the unmarshalling process would have been different, but the end result in the target runtime would be the same.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] The process of unmarshalling XML data into an executable Java object is taken care of by the in-built `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` (formally `javax.xml.bind.Unmarshaller`) class.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods defined in the `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` class are overloaded to accept XML from different types of input such as a `java.io.File`, `java.io.FileInputStream`, or `java.net.URL`.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshal methods can deserialize an entire XML document or a small part of it.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] When the XML root element is globally declared, these methods utilize the `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext`'s mapping of XML root elements to JAXB mapped classes to initiate the unmarshalling.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] If the mappings are not sufficient and the root elements are declared locally, the unmarshal methods use `declaredType` methods for the unmarshalling process.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] These two approaches can be understood below.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal method uses `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.JAXBContext`) to unmarshal the XML data, when the root element is globally declared.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] The `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` object always maintains a mapping of the globally declared XML element and its name to a JAXB mapped class.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] If the XML element name or its `@xsi:type` attribute matches the JAXB mapped class, the unmarshal method transforms the XML data using the appropriate JAXB mapped class.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the XML element name has no match, the unmarshal process will abort and throw an `jakarta.xml.bind.UnmarshalException` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.UnmarshalException`).
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] This can be avoided by using the unmarshal by `declaredType` methods.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] When the root element is not declared globally, the application assists the unmarshaller by application-provided mapping using `declaredType` parameters.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] By an order of precedence, even if the root name has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, the `declaredType` overrides the mapping.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the `@xsi:type` attribute of the XML data has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, then this takes precedence over declaredType parameter.
[src:thrift-idl/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods by `declaredType` parameters always return a `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBElement<T>` instance.
[src:thrift-idl/page] Each supported language needs the Apache Thrift Libraries and the generated code made by the Apache Thrift Compiler.
[src:thrift-idl/page] For a quick introduction that covers a lot of Thrift knowledge on just one page, we recommended Diwaker Gupta’s Thrift: The Missing Guide.
[src:thrift-idl/page] If you want to do a real deep dive into the various language bindings, consider Randy Abernethy’s The Programmer’s Guide to Apache Thrift.
[src:thrift-idl/page] The book comes with a lot of inside knowlegde and is packed with practical examples.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] That is, the programmer writes essentially the same code whether the subroutine is local to the executing program, or remote.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] This is a form of server interaction (caller is client, executor is server), typically implemented via a request–response message passing system.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] In the object-oriented programming paradigm, RPCs are represented by remote method invocation (RMI).
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] The RPC model implies a level of location transparency, namely that calling procedures are largely the same whether they are local or remote, but usually, they are not identical, so local calls can be distinguished from remote calls.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] Remote calls are usually orders of magnitude slower and less reliable than local calls, so distinguishing them is important.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] Many different (often incompatible) technologies have been used to implement the concept.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] Request–response protocols date to early distributed computing in the late 1960s, theoretical proposals of remote procedure calls as the model of network operations date to the 1970s, and practical implementations date to the early 1980s.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] Bruce Jay Nelson is generally credited with coining the term "remote procedure call" in 1981.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] Remote procedure calls used in modern operating systems trace their roots back to the RC 4000 multiprogramming system, which used a request-response communication protocol for process synchronization.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] The idea of treating network operations as remote procedure calls goes back at least to the 1970s in early ARPANET documents.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] In 1978, Per Brinch Hansen proposed Distributed Processes, a language for distributed computing based on "external requests" consisting of procedure calls between processes.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] One of the earliest practical implementations was in 1982 by Brian Randell and colleagues for their Newcastle Connection between UNIX machines.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] This was soon followed by "Lupine" by Andrew Birrell and Bruce Nelson in the Cedar environment at Xerox PARC.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] Lupine automatically generated stubs, providing type-safe bindings, and used an efficient protocol for communication.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] One of the first business uses of RPC was by Xerox under the name "Courier" in 1981.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] The first popular implementation of RPC on Unix was Sun's RPC (now called ONC RPC), used as the basis for Network File System (NFS).
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] In the 1990s, with the popularity of object-oriented programming, an alternative model of remote method invocation (RMI) was widely implemented, such as in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA, 1991) and Java remote method invocation.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] RMIs, in turn, fell in popularity with the rise of the internet, particularly in the 2000s.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] An RPC is initiated by the *client*, which sends a request message to a known remote *server* to execute a specified procedure with supplied parameters.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] The remote server sends a response to the client, and the application continues its process.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] While the server is processing the call, the client is blocked (it waits until the server has finished processing before resuming execution), unless the client sends an asynchronous request to the server, such as an XMLHttpRequest.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] There are many variations and subtleties in various implementations, resulting in a variety of different (incompatible) RPC protocols.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] An important difference between remote procedure calls and local calls is that remote calls can fail because of unpredictable network problems.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] Also, callers generally must deal with such failures without knowing whether the remote procedure was actually invoked.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] Idempotent procedures (those that have no additional effects if called more than once) are easily handled, but enough difficulties remain that code to call remote procedures is often confined to carefully written low-level subsystems.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] The client stub packs the parameters into a message and makes a system call to send the message.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] Packing the parameters is called marshalling.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] The client's local operating system sends the message from the client machine to the server machine.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] The local operating system on the server machine passes the incoming packets to the server stub.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] The server stub unpacks the parameters from the message.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] Unpacking the parameters is called unmarshalling.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] Finally, the server stub calls the server procedure.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] The reply traces the same steps in the reverse direction.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] To let different clients access servers, a number of standardized RPC systems have been created.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] Most of these use an interface description language (IDL) to let various platforms call the RPC.
[src:thrift-idl/remote-procedure-call] The IDL files can then be used to generate code to interface between the client and servers.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:thrift-idl/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
